  {
    title: 'Backend systems',
    body:
      'Python, Django, Rails, Postgres. Production reliability and observability are part of the deliverable. Recent work has spanned Toggle homeowners insurance document templating at Sure (adapting contractor HTML and CSS to carrier-required PDFs) and the migration of a fare-recalculation tool at Lyft off a legacy internal service, integrating with seven downstream services across backend and frontend teams.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Data pipelines & ETL',
    body:
      "Dagster, custom ingestion, and the messy real-world data sources with undocumented contracts that nobody wants to own. Per-state Dagster pipelines for a healthcare credentialing platform at Axuall, ingesting from SFTP feeds, REST APIs, and Selenium-driven web scraping. Before that, a Python WSGI service at Skupos that automated POS data quality troubleshooting and helped scale onboarding from 3,000 retailer locations to between 7,000 and 10,000 without growing the analyst team.",
  },
  {
    title: 'Cross-team product work',
    body:
      "Interfaces between engineering, ops, and external vendors. Migrations and deprecations. Led a third-party rebooking API integration at Lyft from ideation through deployment, which included identifying regressions in the vendor's API and driving their backend team to ship contract-level changes Lyft needed. The transferable skill in work like this is negotiating technical changes across organizational lines without authority.",
  },
  {
    title: 'AI-assisted development advocacy',
    body:
      "Modeling Claude in feature planning, PR review, and PR description authorship until the team adopts the practice and makes it part of how they ship. At Scotch, this is how the engineering team moved from skepticism to muscle memory inside the contract window. I'm honest about what AI tools do and don't help with, and I review every change before it lands.",
  },
